The Producer-Consumer problem is a classic synchronization challenge where multiple threads work with shared resources. Producers add items to a bounded buffer while consumers remove them. The key challenge is preventing producers from adding to a full buffer and consumers from removing from an empty buffer.

The traditional solution uses wait() and notify() methods with synchronization. Here's a robust implementation using BlockingQueue, which is the recommended modern approach:

```java
import java.util.concurrent.BlockingQueue;
import java.util.concurrent.LinkedBlockingQueue;

public class ProducerConsumerExample {
    static class Producer extends Thread {
        private BlockingQueue<Integer> queue;

        public Producer(BlockingQueue<Integer> queue) {
            this.queue = queue;
        }

        @Override
        public void run() {
            try {
                for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
                    System.out.println("Producing: " + i);
                    queue.put(i); // Blocks if queue is full
                    Thread.sleep(500);
                }
            } catch (InterruptedException e) {
                Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
            }
        }
    }

    static class Consumer extends Thread {
        private BlockingQueue<Integer> queue;

        public Consumer(BlockingQueue<Integer> queue) {
            this.queue = queue;
        }

        @Override
        public void run() {
            try {
                while (true) {
                    Integer item = queue.take(); // Blocks if queue is empty
                    System.out.println("Consumed: " + item);
                    Thread.sleep(1000);
                }
            } catch (InterruptedException e) {
                Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
            }
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {
        BlockingQueue<Integer> queue = new LinkedBlockingQueue<>(5);
        new Producer(queue).start();
        new Consumer(queue).start();
    }
}
```

BlockingQueue internally handles synchronization and provides methods like put() and take() that block appropriately. This pattern is essential in real-world scenarios like thread pools, message queues (Kafka), and async task processing. The key insight is that BlockingQueue abstracts away manual synchronization complexity while providing thread-safe operations.

Designing high-performance multithreading requires careful consideration of synchronization, resource contention, and throughput optimization. Key principles include minimizing lock contention, choosing appropriate collection types, and understanding Java's memory model.

Here's a comprehensive example demonstrating best practices:

```java
import java.util.concurrent.*;
import java.util.concurrent.atomic.AtomicLong;
import java.util.concurrent.locks.ReadWriteLock;
import java.util.concurrent.locks.ReentrantReadWriteLock;

public class HighPerformanceThreading {
    // AtomicLong for lock-free counters
    private AtomicLong counter = new AtomicLong(0);

    // ReadWriteLock for read-heavy workloads
    private ReadWriteLock lock = new ReentrantReadWriteLock();
    private volatile boolean running = true;

    // ConcurrentHashMap for thread-safe collections
    private ConcurrentHashMap<String, Long> metrics = new ConcurrentHashMap<>();

    public void incrementCounter() {
        counter.incrementAndGet();
    }

    public long getCounter() {
        return counter.get();
    }

    public void readMetric(String key) {
        lock.readLock().lock();
        try {
            metrics.getOrDefault(key, 0L);
        } finally {
            lock.readLock().unlock();
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        HighPerformanceThreading app = new HighPerformanceThreading();
        ExecutorService executor = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(4);

        // Submit 100 tasks
        for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++) {
            executor.submit(() -> {
                for (int j = 0; j < 1000; j++) {
                    app.incrementCounter();
                }
            });
        }

        executor.shutdown();
        executor.awaitTermination(5, TimeUnit.SECONDS);
        System.out.println("Final count: " + app.getCounter());
    }
}
```

Key optimization strategies: Use AtomicInteger/AtomicLong for simple counters instead of synchronized blocks; leverage ConcurrentHashMap which uses segment-level locking; use ReadWriteLock for read-heavy scenarios; minimize lock holding time; avoid nested locks; use ThreadLocal for thread-confined data; profile with tools like JProfiler before optimizing.

Dependency Injection (DI) is a design pattern that promotes loose coupling by providing dependencies to a class rather than having the class create them. Spring Framework is the de-facto standard for DI in Java.

DI Types:
1. Constructor Injection (Recommended)
2. Setter Injection
3. Field Injection (Discouraged)

Here's a comprehensive example:

```java
import org.springframework.stereotype.Component;
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;

// Constructor Injection - BEST PRACTICE
@Component
public class UserService {
    private final UserRepository userRepository;
    private final EmailService emailService;

    // Constructor injection - makes dependencies explicit and testable
    @Autowired
    public UserService(UserRepository userRepository, EmailService emailService) {
        this.userRepository = userRepository;
        this.emailService = emailService;
    }

    public void registerUser(String email) {
        userRepository.save(email);
        emailService.sendWelcomeEmail(email);
    }
}

@Component
public class UserRepository {
    public void save(String email) {
        // Save user
    }
}

@Component
public class EmailService {
    public void sendWelcomeEmail(String email) {
        // Send email
    }
}

// Testing with DI
public class UserServiceTest {
    @Test
    public void testRegisterUser() {
        UserRepository mockRepo = Mockito.mock(UserRepository.class);
        EmailService mockEmail = Mockito.mock(EmailService.class);

        UserService service = new UserService(mockRepo, mockEmail);
        service.registerUser("test@example.com");

        Mockito.verify(mockEmail).sendWelcomeEmail("test@example.com");
    }
}
```

Why Constructor Injection is superior: Dependencies are immutable (final); makes required dependencies explicit; improves testability; prevents partial initialization; handles circular dependencies better. Avoid field injection as it makes unit testing harder and creates hidden dependencies.

Spring Boot annotations simplify configuration and component discovery. Here are the most important ones:

```java
// Core Component Annotations
@Component          // Generic component
@Service            // Business logic layer
@Repository         // Data access layer
@Controller         // Web controllers (returns views)
@RestController     // REST endpoints (returns JSON)

// Configuration & Properties
@Configuration      // Defines configuration class
@PropertySource     // Load external properties
@ConfigurationProperties  // Bind properties to bean
@Value("${property.name}") // Inject single property

// Dependency Injection
@Autowired          // Auto-wire dependencies
@Qualifier          // Specify which bean to inject
@Primary            // Default bean when multiple exist

// Lifecycle & Initialization
@PostConstruct      // Execute after bean construction
@PreDestroy         // Execute before bean destruction
@Bean               // Define bean in configuration class

// Example Usage
@SpringBootApplication
public class Application {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(Application.class, args);
    }
}

@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/users")
public class UserController {
    @Autowired
    private UserService userService;

    @GetMapping("/{id}")
    public ResponseEntity<User> getUser(@PathVariable Long id) {
        return ResponseEntity.ok(userService.findById(id));
    }
}

@Service
public class UserService {
    @Autowired
    private UserRepository repository;

    public User findById(Long id) {
        return repository.findById(id).orElse(null);
    }
}

@Repository
public class UserRepository extends JpaRepository<User, Long> {
}
```

Key annotation differences: @Service vs @Repository vs @Component - all are equivalent functionally but signal intent; @Controller returns views while @RestController returns JSON directly; @Bean is used for manual configuration while @Component enables auto-discovery.

@Component, @Service, and @Repository are all Spring stereotypes that enable component auto-discovery. While functionally equivalent, they differ in semantic meaning and exception translation.

```java
// 1. @Component - Generic component
@Component
public class GenericComponent {
    public void doSomething() {
        System.out.println("Generic work");
    }
}

// 2. @Service - Business logic layer
@Service
public class UserService {
    private UserRepository repository;

    @Autowired
    public UserService(UserRepository repository) {
        this.repository = repository;
    }

    public void registerUser(User user) {
        // Business logic
        repository.save(user);
    }
}

// 3. @Repository - Data access layer with exception translation
@Repository
public class UserRepository {
    @Autowired
    private JdbcTemplate jdbc;

    public void save(User user) {
        // Spring translates database exceptions to DataAccessException hierarchy
        jdbc.update("INSERT INTO users VALUES (?, ?)", user.getName());
    }
}

// Best Practice Example
@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/users")
public class UserController {  // Note: No @Component needed
    @Autowired
    private UserService service; // Inject service, not repository

    @PostMapping
    public ResponseEntity<User> create(@RequestBody User user) {
        service.registerUser(user);
        return ResponseEntity.ok(user);
    }
}
```

Key differences:
- @Component: Generic, used when role is unclear
- @Service: Marks business logic layer, semantically indicates service
- @Repository: Data access layer with PersistenceExceptionTranslator support (converts checked DB exceptions to unchecked DataAccessException)

In practice, all three register beans in Spring context, but @Repository adds exception translation which is crucial for database operations. Always use @Service for business logic and @Repository for data access to maintain clear architecture and proper exception handling.

Constructor Injection and Field Injection are two ways to inject dependencies. Constructor Injection is the recommended approach in modern Spring applications.

```java
// BAD: Field Injection - Avoid this in production
@Service
public class BadUserService {
    @Autowired
    private UserRepository repository; // Hard to test, hidden dependency

    public void saveUser(User user) {
        repository.save(user);
    }
}

// Problematic for testing - must use reflection or Spring test framework
@Test
public void testFieldInjectio() {
    BadUserService service = new BadUserService();
    // Cannot easily mock UserRepository - must use @ExtendWith(SpringExtension.class)
    // service.repository = mockRepository; // Reflection needed
}

// GOOD: Constructor Injection - Recommended
@Service
public class GoodUserService {
    private final UserRepository repository;
    private final EmailService emailService;

    // Dependencies explicit and final
    @Autowired // @Autowired can be omitted in Spring 4.3+
    public GoodUserService(UserRepository repository, EmailService emailService) {
        this.repository = repository;
        this.emailService = emailService;
    }

    public void registerUser(User user) {
        repository.save(user);
        emailService.sendWelcomeEmail(user.getEmail());
    }
}

// Easy to test - no Spring needed
@Test
public void testConstructorInjection() {
    UserRepository mockRepo = Mockito.mock(UserRepository.class);
    EmailService mockEmail = Mockito.mock(EmailService.class);

    GoodUserService service = new GoodUserService(mockRepo, mockEmail);
    service.registerUser(new User("test@example.com"));

    verify(mockEmail).sendWelcomeEmail("test@example.com");
}

// Optional: Setter Injection (middle ground, rarely used)
@Service
public class OptionalService {
    private UserRepository repository;

    @Autowired
    public void setRepository(UserRepository repository) {
        this.repository = repository; // Dependencies not required
    }
}
```

Advantages of Constructor Injection:
- Dependencies are explicit and immutable (final fields)
- Makes required dependencies clear
- Easy unit testing without Spring framework
- Prevents circular dependency issues
- NullPointerExceptions caught at construction time, not at runtime

Disadvantages of Field Injection:
- Hidden dependencies that aren't obvious
- Requires Spring context for testing
- NullPointerException at runtime if dependency not found
- Cannot make fields immutable (final)
- Harder to test in isolation

Spring uses Proxy pattern extensively for cross-cutting concerns like @Transactional, @Cacheable, and AOP. Understanding proxies is crucial for debugging Spring applications.

Spring supports two types of proxies:
1. JDK Dynamic Proxy (interface-based)
2. CGLIB Proxy (class-based)

```java
// Example: @Transactional uses proxies
@Service
public class UserService {
    @Autowired
    private UserRepository repository;

    // Spring creates proxy around this method
    @Transactional
    public User registerUser(User user) {
        repository.save(user);
        // Proxy handles transaction management
        return user;
    }
}

// Proxy mechanism illustration
public class TransactionalProxy implements UserService {
    private UserService target;
    private TransactionManager tm;

    public User registerUser(User user) {
        // Proxy logic
        Transaction tx = tm.begin();
        try {
            User result = target.registerUser(user);
            tx.commit();
            return result;
        } catch (Exception e) {
            tx.rollback();
            throw e;
        }
    }
}

// Common Proxy Issues
@Service
public class ProxyIssuesDemo {
    @Transactional
    public void method1() {
        method2(); // PROBLEM: Calls real object, not proxy!
    }

    @Transactional
    public void method2() {
        // Transaction not active here if called from method1
    }

    // SOLUTION: Inject self
    @Autowired
    private ProxyIssuesDemo self;

    @Transactional
    public void method1Fixed() {
        self.method2(); // CORRECT: Calls proxy
    }
}

// Verify which proxy type is used
@Component
public class ProxyChecker {
    @PostConstruct
    public void checkProxy() {
        System.out.println("Class: " + this.getClass().getName());
        // Output: com.example.ProxyChecker$Proxy (CGLIB)
        // or: com.sun.proxy.$Proxy123 (JDK Dynamic Proxy)

        System.out.println("Is Proxy: " + this.getClass().getName().contains("$")); 
    }
}
```

Key points: Spring creates proxies automatically for annotated methods; proxies intercept calls for @Transactional, @Cacheable, @Async, etc.; JDK proxies require interfaces; CGLIB proxies work with classes but slower; self-invocation bypasses proxy; always be aware of proxy behavior when debugging.

Aspect-Oriented Programming (AOP) in Spring enables cross-cutting concerns like logging, security, caching to be applied declaratively without modifying business code.

Core AOP Concepts:
- Aspect: Reusable module of cross-cutting behavior
- Pointcut: Expression matching join points
- Advice: Code executed at join points
- Join Point: Point in execution where aspect is applied

```java
// 1. Custom Annotation
@Target(ElementType.METHOD)
@Retention(RetentionPolicy.RUNTIME)
public @interface Loggable {
    String value() default "";
}

// 2. Aspect Definition
@Aspect
@Component
public class LoggingAspect {

    // Pointcut expression
    @Pointcut("@annotation(com.example.Loggable)")
    public void loggableMethod() {}

    // Before advice
    @Before("loggableMethod()")
    public void before(JoinPoint joinPoint) {
        String methodName = joinPoint.getSignature().getName();
        System.out.println("Before: " + methodName);
    }

    // After advice
    @After("loggableMethod()")
    public void after(JoinPoint joinPoint) {
        String methodName = joinPoint.getSignature().getName();
        System.out.println("After: " + methodName);
    }

    // Around advice (most powerful)
    @Around("loggableMethod()")
    public Object around(ProceedingJoinPoint joinPoint) throws Throwable {
        long start = System.currentTimeMillis();
        try {
            Object result = joinPoint.proceed(); // Execute actual method
            return result;
        } finally {
            long duration = System.currentTimeMillis() - start;
            System.out.println("Execution time: " + duration + "ms");
        }
    }
}

// 3. Business Service using AOP
@Service
public class UserService {

    @Loggable("Registering user")
    public void registerUser(User user) {
        // Business logic - logging handled by aspect
        System.out.println("User registered: " + user.getEmail());
    }

    @Loggable("Fetching user")
    public User getUser(Long id) {
        return new User(id, "test@example.com");
    }
}

// 4. Pointcut Examples
@Aspect
public class PointcutExamples {
    // Match all methods in package
    @Pointcut("execution(* com.example.service.*.*(..))") 
    public void serviceLayer() {}

    // Match methods with annotation
    @Pointcut("@annotation(org.springframework.transaction.annotation.Transactional)")
    public void transactionalMethods() {}

    // Match methods taking String argument
    @Pointcut("execution(* *(.., String, ..))") 
    public void methodsWithString() {}

    // Complex pointcut combining multiple
    @Pointcut("serviceLayer() && transactionalMethods()")
    public void serviceTransactional() {}
}
```

Common Advice Types:
- @Before: Execute before method
- @After: Execute after method (regardless of outcome)
- @AfterReturning: Execute after successful return
- @AfterThrowing: Execute if exception thrown
- @Around: Execute before and after (can modify args/return)

Real-world use cases: Performance monitoring, security checks, transaction management, caching, audit logging.

REST (Representational State Transfer) and SOAP (Simple Object Access Protocol) are two approaches for building web services. REST is modern and widely preferred, while SOAP is older and more formal.

Key Differences:

```
REST (Modern)           SOAP (Legacy)
- Lightweight           - Heavy (XML with envelope)
- Uses HTTP methods     - Custom protocol
- Stateless            - Can be stateful
- JSON/XML             - Only XML
- Resource-oriented    - Operation-oriented
- Easy to use          - Complex setup
- Better performance   - Slower
```

```java
// REST Example - Recommended
@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/users")
public class UserRestController {
    @Autowired
    private UserService userService;

    @GetMapping("/{id}")     // GET /api/users/123
    public ResponseEntity<User> getUser(@PathVariable Long id) {
        return ResponseEntity.ok(userService.findById(id));
    }

    @PostMapping              // POST /api/users
    public ResponseEntity<User> createUser(@RequestBody User user) {
        User saved = userService.save(user);
        return ResponseEntity.status(201).body(saved);
    }

    @PutMapping("/{id}")      // PUT /api/users/123
    public ResponseEntity<User> updateUser(@PathVariable Long id, @RequestBody User user) {
        return ResponseEntity.ok(userService.update(id, user));
    }

    @DeleteMapping("/{id}")   // DELETE /api/users/123
    public ResponseEntity<Void> deleteUser(@PathVariable Long id) {
        userService.delete(id);
        return ResponseEntity.noContent().build();
    }
}

// REST Response
/*
GET /api/users/1 HTTP/1.1

Response:
{
  "id": 1,
  "name": "John",
  "email": "john@example.com"
}
*/

// SOAP Example - Legacy
/*
POST /ws/UserService HTTP/1.1
Content-Type: application/soap+xml

<?xml version="1.0"?>
<soap:Envelope xmlns:soap="http://schemas.xmlsoap.org/soap/envelope/">
  <soap:Body>
    <GetUser xmlns="http://example.com/users">
      <id>1</id>
    </GetUser>
  </soap:Body>
</soap:Envelope>

Response:
<?xml version="1.0"?>
<soap:Envelope>
  <soap:Body>
    <GetUserResponse>
      <user>
        <id>1</id>
        <name>John</name>
      </user>
    </GetUserResponse>
  </soap:Body>
</soap:Envelope>
*/
```

When to use:
- REST: Modern applications, microservices, mobile apps, public APIs (preferred)
- SOAP: Legacy systems, complex transactions, formal contracts, highly regulated industries (compliance-heavy)

REST advantages: Simple HTTP methods, stateless, cacheable, browser-friendly, JSON support, easier testing.
SOAP advantages: Formal contracts (WSDL), security standards (WS-Security), guaranteed delivery, better for complex operations.

Spring Boot AutoConfiguration automatically configures Spring application based on classpath dependencies. This eliminates manual configuration, enabling convention over configuration.

How AutoConfiguration Works:

```java
// 1. @SpringBootApplication enables auto-configuration
@SpringBootApplication  // Includes @EnableAutoConfiguration
public class Application {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        SpringApplication.run(Application.class, args);
    }
}

// 2. AutoConfiguration Classes (in spring-boot-autoconfigure)
// When JPA and H2 are on classpath, Spring auto-configures DataSource
@Configuration
@ConditionalOnClass(DataSource.class)
@EnableConfigurationProperties(DataSourceProperties.class)
public class DataSourceAutoConfiguration {

    @Bean
    @ConditionalOnMissingBean
    public DataSource dataSource() {
        return createDataSource();
    }
}

// 3. Conditional Annotations
@Configuration
public class ConditionalExamples {

    // Only if MyClass is on classpath
    @ConditionalOnClass(MyClass.class)
    public void configureWhenClassPresent() {}

    // Only if property exists
    @ConditionalOnProperty(name = "app.feature.enabled", havingValue = "true")
    public void configureWhenPropertyTrue() {}

    // Only if bean doesn't exist
    @ConditionalOnMissingBean
    @Bean
    public MyService myService() {
        return new MyService();
    }

    // Conditional on Java version
    @ConditionalOnJava(JavaVersion.NINE_OR_LATER)
    public void configureForJava9Plus() {}
}

// 4. View AutoConfiguration (application.properties)
application.properties:
# Override auto-configuration
server.port=8080
spring.datasource.url=jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/mydb
spring.datasource.username=root
spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto=update

// 5. Disable Specific AutoConfiguration
@SpringBootApplication(exclude = DataSourceAutoConfiguration.class)
public class Application {
}

// Or in properties
spring.autoconfigure.exclude=\
  org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.jdbc.DataSourceAutoConfiguration,\
  org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.orm.jpa.HibernateJpaAutoConfiguration

// 6. Custom AutoConfiguration
@Configuration
@ConditionalOnClass(MyService.class)
@ConditionalOnProperty(
    name = "app.custom.enabled",
    havingValue = "true",
    matchIfMissing = true
)
public class MyCustomAutoConfiguration {

    @Bean
    @ConditionalOnMissingBean
    public MyService myService() {
        return new MyService();
    }
}

// Register in META-INF/spring.factories:
/*
org.springframework.boot.autoconfigure.EnableAutoConfiguration=\
com.example.MyCustomAutoConfiguration
*/
```

AutoConfiguration uses SpringFactoriesLoader to discover configuration classes from META-INF/spring.factories. Conditional annotations determine whether configuration applies. Spring Boot provides 50+ auto-configurations that activate based on dependencies (Spring Data, MongoDB, Redis, etc.).

Spring Security provides authentication and authorization through a filter chain. Understanding the flow is essential for implementing security properly.

Security Flow Steps:
1. Request -> DelegatingFilterProxy
2. FilterChainProxy
3. Authentication Filter
4. AuthenticationManager
5. AuthenticationProvider
6. UserDetailsService
7. GrantedAuthority

```java
// 1. Security Configuration
@Configuration
@EnableWebSecurity
public class SecurityConfig extends WebSecurityConfigurerAdapter {

    @Bean
    public PasswordEncoder passwordEncoder() {
        return new BCryptPasswordEncoder();
    }

    @Override
    protected void configure(AuthenticationManagerBuilder auth) throws Exception {
        // AuthenticationManager configuration
        auth
            .userDetailsService(userDetailsService())
            .passwordEncoder(passwordEncoder());
    }

    @Bean
    public UserDetailsService userDetailsService() {
        return new CustomUserDetailsService();
    }

    @Override
    protected void configure(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {
        http
            .csrf().disable()
            .authorizeRequests()
                .antMatchers("/public/**").permitAll()
                .antMatchers("/admin/**").hasRole("ADMIN")
                .anyRequest().authenticated()
            .and()
            .formLogin()
                .loginPage("/login")
                .defaultSuccessUrl("/home")
            .and()
            .logout()
                .logoutSuccessUrl("/");
    }
}

// 2. UserDetails Service
@Service
public class CustomUserDetailsService implements UserDetailsService {

    @Autowired
    private UserRepository userRepository;

    @Override
    public UserDetails loadUserByUsername(String username) throws UsernameNotFoundException {
        User user = userRepository.findByUsername(username)
            .orElseThrow(() -> new UsernameNotFoundException("User not found"));

        return org.springframework.security.core.userdetails.User.builder()
            .username(user.getUsername())
            .password(user.getPassword())
            .authorities(getAuthorities(user))
            .accountExpired(false)
            .accountLocked(false)
            .credentialsExpired(false)
            .disabled(false)
            .build();
    }

    private List<GrantedAuthority> getAuthorities(User user) {
        return user.getRoles().stream()
            .map(role -> new SimpleGrantedAuthority("ROLE_" + role.getName()))
            .collect(Collectors.toList());
    }
}

// 3. Authentication Filter Flow
@Component
public class JwtAuthenticationFilter extends OncePerRequestFilter {

    @Autowired
    private JwtTokenProvider tokenProvider;

    @Autowired
    private UserDetailsService userDetailsService;

    @Override
    protected void doFilterInternal(HttpServletRequest request,
                                    HttpServletResponse response,
                                    FilterChain filterChain) throws ServletException, IOException {
        try {
            String jwt = extractJwtFromRequest(request);
            if (jwt != null && tokenProvider.validateToken(jwt)) {
                String username = tokenProvider.getUsernameFromToken(jwt);
                UserDetails userDetails = userDetailsService.loadUserByUsername(username);

                // Create Authentication object
                UsernamePasswordAuthenticationToken auth =
                    new UsernamePasswordAuthenticationToken(
                        userDetails, null, userDetails.getAuthorities());

                // Set in SecurityContext
                SecurityContextHolder.getContext().setAuthentication(auth);
            }
        } catch (Exception e) {
            logger.error("Could not set authentication", e);
        }

        filterChain.doFilter(request, response);
    }
}

// 4. Authorization Annotation
@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api")
public class SecureController {

    @GetMapping("/user")
    @PreAuthorize("hasRole('USER')")
    public String userData(Authentication auth) {
        return "User: " + auth.getName();
    }

    @GetMapping("/admin")
    @PreAuthorize("hasRole('ADMIN')")
    public String adminData() {
        return "Admin data";
    }

    @GetMapping("/public")
    @PermitAll
    public String publicData() {
        return "Public data";
    }
}
```

Key Components:
- SecurityContext: Holds Authentication object
- AuthenticationManager: Orchestrates authentication
- AuthenticationProvider: Performs actual authentication
- UserDetailsService: Loads user details from database
- GrantedAuthority: Represents permissions/roles
- FilterChain: Applies multiple filters in sequence

OAuth2 is an authorization framework enabling applications to obtain limited access to user accounts on an HTTP service. It's widely used for third-party integrations and API access.

OAuth2 Grant Types:
1. Authorization Code (Most common)
2. Implicit
3. Client Credentials
4. Resource Owner Password

```java
// OAuth2 Authorization Code Flow
/*
1. User clicks "Login with Google"
2. Redirect to Google: /oauth/authorize?client_id=...&redirect_uri=...
3. User grants permission
4. Google redirects to: /callback?code=auth_code
5. Backend exchanges code for access token (server-to-server)
6. Access token used to fetch user info
7. User authenticated and logged in
*/

// Spring OAuth2 Resource Server Configuration
@Configuration
@EnableResourceServer
public class ResourceServerConfig extends ResourceServerConfigurerAdapter {

    @Override
    public void configure(HttpSecurity http) throws Exception {
        http
            .csrf().disable()
            .authorizeRequests()
                .antMatchers("/public/**").permitAll()
                .antMatchers("/api/**").authenticated()
            .and()
            .oauth2ResourceServer()
                .jwt();
    }
}

// OAuth2 Authorization Server (Deprecated in Spring Security 5.1+)
@Configuration
@EnableAuthorizationServer
public class AuthorizationServerConfig extends AuthorizationServerConfigurerAdapter {

    @Autowired
    private AuthenticationManager authenticationManager;

    @Override
    public void configure(AuthorizationServerSecurityConfigurer security) throws Exception {
        security.checkTokenAccess("isAuthenticated()");
    }

    @Override
    public void configure(ClientDetailsServiceConfigurer clients) throws Exception {
        clients.inMemory()
            .withClient("my-app")
            .secret(passwordEncoder().encode("secret"))
            .authorizedGrantTypes("authorization_code", "refresh_token")
            .scopes("read", "write")
            .redirectUris("http://localhost:8080/callback");
    }

    @Override
    public void configure(AuthorizationServerEndpointsConfigurer endpoints) throws Exception {
        endpoints.authenticationManager(authenticationManager);
    }

    @Bean
    public PasswordEncoder passwordEncoder() {
        return new BCryptPasswordEncoder();
    }
}

