Event-Driven Patterns: Choreography (services listen and react directly), Orchestration (central coordinator), CQRS (separate read/write models), Sagas (distributed transactions).

The Saga Pattern manages distributed transactions across microservices without distributed locks. It uses a sequence of local transactions with compensating transactions for failures.

Two approaches: Choreography (event-driven) and Orchestration (coordinator).

```java
// 1. Choreography-Based Saga (Events trigger next step)
@Service
public class OrderSagaChoreography {

    @Autowired
    private KafkaTemplate<String, String> kafkaTemplate;

    // Step 1: Order created
    @Transactional
    @PostMapping("/orders")
    public Order createOrder(OrderRequest request) {
        Order order = new Order();
        order.setStatus("PENDING");
        orderRepository.save(order);

        // Emit event
        publishEvent("order.created", order);
        return order;
    }

    // Step 2: Listen to order.created and create payment
    @KafkaListener(topics = "order.created")
    @Transactional
    public void reservePayment(OrderCreatedEvent event) {
        try {
            Payment payment = paymentService.reserve(event.getOrderId(), event.getAmount());
            publishEvent("payment.reserved", payment);
        } catch (PaymentException e) {
            // Compensation: Cancel order
            publishEvent("order.cancelled", event.getOrderId());
        }
    }

    // Step 3: Listen to payment.reserved and reserve inventory
    @KafkaListener(topics = "payment.reserved")
    @Transactional
    public void reserveInventory(PaymentReservedEvent event) {
        try {
            inventoryService.reserve(event.getOrderId());
            publishEvent("inventory.reserved", event.getOrderId());
        } catch (InventoryException e) {
            // Compensation: Release payment
            publishEvent("payment.released", event.getOrderId());
        }
    }

    // Step 4: Confirm order
    @KafkaListener(topics = "inventory.reserved")
    @Transactional
    public void confirmOrder(String orderId) {
        orderRepository.updateStatus(orderId, "CONFIRMED");
    }

    // Compensation: Cancel order
    @KafkaListener(topics = "order.cancelled")
    @Transactional
    public void compensateOrder(String orderId) {
        orderRepository.updateStatus(orderId, "CANCELLED");
    }

    // Compensation: Release payment
    @KafkaListener(topics = "payment.released")
    @Transactional
    public void compensatePayment(String orderId) {
        paymentService.release(orderId);
    }
}

// 2. Orchestration-Based Saga (Coordinator orchestrates)
@Service
public class OrderSagaOrchestrator {

    @Autowired
    private OrderService orderService;

    @Autowired
    private PaymentService paymentService;

    @Autowired
    private InventoryService inventoryService;

    @Transactional
    public void executeOrderSaga(OrderRequest request) {
        // Step 1: Create order
        Order order = orderService.create(request);

        try {
            // Step 2: Reserve payment
            Payment payment = paymentService.reserve(order.getId(), order.getAmount());

            try {
                // Step 3: Reserve inventory
                inventoryService.reserve(order.getId());

                // Step 4: Confirm order
                orderService.confirm(order.getId());
            } catch (InventoryException e) {
                // Compensation: Release payment
                paymentService.release(payment.getId());
                throw e;
            }
        } catch (PaymentException e) {
            // Compensation: Cancel order
            orderService.cancel(order.getId());
            throw e;
        }
    }
}

// 3. Saga State Machine (More Robust)
@Configuration
public class OrderSagaStateMachine {

    @Bean
    public StateMachine<SagaState, SagaEvent> sagaStateMachine(
        StateMachineFactory<SagaState, SagaEvent> factory) {
        return factory.getStateMachine("orderSaga");
    }
}

public enum SagaState {
    PENDING, PAYMENT_RESERVED, INVENTORY_RESERVED, CONFIRMED, CANCELLED
}

public enum SagaEvent {
    ORDER_CREATED, PAYMENT_RESERVED, INVENTORY_RESERVED,
    PAYMENT_FAILED, INVENTORY_FAILED
}

// 4. Idempotency for Saga Steps
@Component
public class IdempotentSagaStep {

    @Autowired
    private SagaStepRepository stepRepository;

    @Transactional
    public void executeStep(String sagaId, String stepName, Runnable action) {
        // Check if step already executed
        if (stepRepository.findBySagaIdAndStepName(sagaId, stepName).isPresent()) {
            return; // Already executed, skip
        }

        // Execute step
        action.run();

        // Record completion
        stepRepository.save(new SagaStep(sagaId, stepName, LocalDateTime.now()));
    }
}

// 5. Timeout and Deadlock Prevention
@Component
public class SagaTimeout {

    @Scheduled(fixedDelay = 60000) // 1 minute
    @Transactional
    public void checkSagaTimeouts() {
        List<String> timedOutSagas = sagaRepository.findTimedOut(Duration.ofMinutes(30));

        for (String sagaId : timedOutSagas) {
            // Trigger compensation
            compensateSaga(sagaId);
        }
    }
}
```

Saga Considerations: Idempotency (executions must be repeatable), compensating transactions (undo logic), eventual consistency (temporary inconsistency acceptable), monitoring (track saga progress).

Distributed Tracing tracks requests across multiple microservices, providing visibility into system behavior and performance bottlenecks.

Key concepts: Trace ID (request identifier), Span (operation in service), Parent-Child relationships.

